(ordinary-world-weather-work
  :count 8

  (piece
    :id \"ww-01-october\"
    :title \"October\"
    :prose
    \"October in New York is the best month. The trees turn. The air is
cold in the morning and warm by noon. Everyone is out in coats but
carrying them by afternoon.

The park is full on Saturdays. Everyone knows they only have a few
more good weekends before the winter. The kids kick soccer balls. The
adults walk in twos and threes. The dogs are extra enthusiastic
because the temperature suits them.

The pumpkin spice thing is a joke and also real. The line at the
coffee shop is longer than usual. The scarves come out. The boots
come out.

At night the temperature drops. You put on a heavier jacket. You
notice your breath.

By the last week of the month the leaves are on the ground more than
the trees. The rakes come out. Someone in every block hires a kid to
rake. Someone else does it themselves and complains cheerfully.

The kids in kindergarten make window decorations. The colder mornings
smell like coffee and wet leaves and something else that is just
October.

The world is beautiful in October. Everyone knows. Nobody says it too
much or it will lose the shape.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-02-a-heat-wave\"
    :title \"A heat wave\"
    :prose
    \"Three days of ninety-eight degrees. The city becomes a slower
version of itself.

The AC in the bodega is set to sixty-eight. The owner doesn't care
about the electric bill because customers stay longer and buy more.

The subway platforms are unbearable. Everyone stands as close to the
wall as possible for the tiny piece of shade. When the train pulls
in the wind before it is the best moment of the afternoon.

Old people stay inside. The city sends alerts to check on them. The
neighbors do it too, not because of the alert but because that's what
you do.

Kids in the fire hydrant. Kids in the sprinklers at the park. Kids at
the beach.

Dogs are miserable. Owners walk them at seven in the morning and nine
at night. Nobody walks them at noon.

The old air conditioners hum in every window. The people who don't
have air conditioners go to the library or the movies or a friend's.

On the third night a thunderstorm breaks the heat. Everyone opens
their windows. The rain smells sweet. The temperature drops fifteen
degrees in an hour. The city sleeps well.

The next morning the heat wave is over. It felt like an event while
it was happening. Now it's just a memory. Until the next one.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-03-a-snowstorm\"
    :title \"A snowstorm\"
    :prose
    \"The forecast said six inches. It got twelve. The mayor called a
snow emergency at eight in the morning. Everything closed.

The kids were the most excited. School was canceled. They got up
early anyway. They put on their snow pants — some had them, some
made do with layers. They went to the park across the street. There
were maybe forty kids there by noon.

The adults were more mixed. The people who worked from home were
mostly fine. The people who had to get somewhere were mostly not.
The bus and train service was reduced. Trains ran but slowly.

The plows came around three in the afternoon. The city plows the
main streets first. The side streets get done later. Sometimes not
until the next day. Everyone knew this. Nobody was surprised.

By evening the snow had stopped and the temperature had dropped. The
snow got crunchier. Kids started coming inside. Adults started
digging out cars. Some cars would stay buried for three days because
their owners weren't going anywhere.

The next morning the city was different. Whiter. Quieter. The rooftops
had a foot of snow on them. The trees looked heavy.

The kid down the block got paid twenty dollars to shovel someone's
sidewalk. That was the going rate. He shoveled five sidewalks and
made a hundred dollars and told his mother it was a good day.

That was the whole storm. It happened once and then it faded into
regular winter.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-04-a-slow-work-day\"
    :title \"A slow work day\"
    :prose
    \"Some days at work are slow. The phones don't ring much. The emails
are routine. You get through your inbox by ten and then you have
nothing to do until lunch.

You could take a longer lunch. You could get ahead on things that
have been backlogged. You could reorganize your files. Nobody would
notice.

Or you could take out your phone and scroll for a while and hate
yourself a little.

The office has three of you today. One of the others is on a call.
The other is looking at a spreadsheet.

You go make coffee. You take longer than you need. You put on some
music that you can only listen to when nobody's around. You come
back to your desk.

The mail arrives at two. You have one letter. You open it. It's not
important.

At three the boss comes by. She has three questions. You have three
answers. It takes eight minutes. Then she leaves.

At four you decide you've done enough. You send a status email so it
looks like a full day. You leave at four-thirty.

Some days are slow. Nobody talks about them. Nobody feels good about
them. They're just part of the week.

Tomorrow will be busy. That's usually how it works.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-05-a-fast-work-day\"
    :title \"A fast work day\"
    :prose
    \"You wake up already thinking about work. Three big things due today.
The presentation you haven't finished. The client who is going to
call. The document that has to be reviewed.

You skip breakfast. You get to the office at eight instead of nine.
You start with the presentation because it needs the most brain.

By nine you've got the shape of the presentation but it's not clean.
You keep going.

At nine-thirty the client calls. You take the call in the small
conference room. It's a good call — twenty minutes, no drama. You
get back to the presentation.

At ten-forty-five you send the presentation. It's not perfect but it's
sent.

At eleven you start the document review. Twenty pages. You read it
carefully. You mark two things that need to change. You send it back
by twelve-thirty.

You skip lunch. You eat a granola bar at your desk.

The afternoon is a bunch of small fires. Somebody needs a number.
Somebody needs a signature. Somebody needs your opinion.

By six you're tired. You leave. You get home and don't want to
cook. You order in. You watch something on TV that doesn't require
attention.

You go to bed at ten. You sleep well because you're tired.

That was a good work day. Nothing spectacular. Nothing was broken.
Everything moved.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-06-a-farmer-market\"
    :title \"A farmers market\"
    :prose
    \"Saturday mornings at the farmers market. It's in a small square
that becomes a market between April and November. Twenty vendors.
They start setting up at six. The crowd arrives at eight.

The tomato guy is your favorite. He's an older man from a farm two
hours north. His tomatoes are always better than what's in the
supermarket. You have paid five dollars for one tomato before, without
regret.

The bread guy has a line. His sourdough is famous in the neighborhood.
If you don't get there by nine there won't be any left.

The flower woman sells small bouquets for ten dollars each. Wildflowers.
Nothing fancy. You buy one every weekend if you have the ten dollars.

The honey guy. The mushroom guy. The lady with the pickles. The couple
who makes cheese. The teenager who sells eggs from her family's farm.

You walk the whole market before you decide what to buy. You have
sixty dollars in cash. You buy some tomatoes, a loaf of bread, a bunch
of flowers, and half a dozen eggs. That takes fifty-four dollars. You
put six back in your pocket.

You walk home with the bag. It smells like tomato and basil. You are
in a specific kind of good mood that only Saturday morning at the
market can produce.

By eleven you're home. You'll eat some of the tomatoes today. Some
tomorrow. The bread will last until Tuesday. The flowers will last
until Thursday. The eggs are for the week.

Sixty dollars. A good spend.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-07-a-laundromat\"
    :title \"A laundromat\"
    :prose
    \"The laundromat on Vanderbilt is open twenty-four hours. Most people
go on the weekend. But there are people there all the time.

The woman who runs it during the day is friendly but not chatty. She
knows most of the regulars. She keeps quarters at the counter for the
people who forget to bring them.

The washing machines are big. Big enough for two weeks of laundry.
Everyone who does laundry knows the shape of a two-week wash: three
or four loads, one or two hours per load, then folding.

You sit in a plastic chair and wait. There's a little TV on the wall
playing something with the volume off. The subtitles roll.

You bring a book. You've been meaning to finish it for weeks. You get
through a chapter.

The person next to you is also waiting. Their phone is playing a
video. They apologize and put in earbuds. You nod. They nod back.

At the folding table, at the end, you fold everything. You've done
this so many times that the folding takes ten minutes for a whole
basket.

You carry the folded clothes home. They smell clean. The laundromat
smell — bright and floral and slightly chemical — will be on the
clothes for a day.

It's not a fun trip. It's not exactly a chore either. It's just
laundry. It happens. It gets done.\")

  (piece
    :id \"ww-08-a-small-shop\"
    :title \"A small shop\"
    :prose
    \"The store on the corner sells a little of everything: chips,
candy, phone chargers, batteries, lottery tickets, sodas, aspirin,
sunscreen in summer, gloves in winter.

The owner is Bengali. He has been on this corner for eighteen years.
He knows most of the customers. The customers know him. Some know
his family. Some remember when his kids were small.

The store is small. Six aisles. The counter is at the front. Behind
the counter there is a wall of small items and the lottery machine.

The margins on most things are thin. The margins on lottery tickets
are okay. Everything else keeps the lights on.

The owner works six days a week. His son works the seventh. The son
is in college for engineering. He works the store on Sundays to give
his father a day off.

The lottery is popular. The owner has sold three winning tickets over
his eighteen years. Two small (five thousand and two thousand). One
larger (forty-two thousand). The winners always come back and tell
him. Twice they gave him a small gift as thanks.

Customers come in for something specific. They leave with something
specific plus something they didn't plan on. That's the whole
economics of a corner store. The unplanned item on the way out is
the margin.

The store is unglamorous. It works. It has worked for eighteen years.
It will work for eighteen more if the rent doesn't go up too much.\"))
")
